Hope this was helpful! The goal of this thread was to explain L2's in such a way that crypto newbies will understand them.

For an in-depth look into Ethereum scaling:

https://t.co/W95iUJQph2

Here's a great read on rollups from @VitalikButerin himself:

https://t.co/CHdTuNA2cO

In short, Layer 2's solve Ethereum's pain points like high gas fees and slow speeds, without sacrificing on security.

Ethereum's Layer 2 ecosystem is incredibly vibrant - as shown in this visual by @deversifi: https://t.co/END8tJidXG

In brief, ZK Rollups are more sophisticated - more efficient with higher transaction rates - but require more computing power, which is not ideal for smaller applications with less activity

For a much more technical deep-dive, this is a great resource:

https://t.co/QJuC0kxPIV

There are two types of rollups.

Optimistic Rollups (like Arbitrum) and the more popular Zero-knowledge (ZK) Rollups (like Polygon, Immutable X and Loopring)

Rollups reduce gas fees by executing transactions off of layer 1.

They are highly secure because the data and proof of transactions still reside on layer 1.

This data stored on L1 can interact with the rollup smart contract on L2 to enforce proper transaction execution.

How do these work, in simplest terms?

Layer 2 is basically compressing a bunch of transactions, then posting the data to Layer 1, instead of processing each transaction individually.

These are called rollups.

This is obviously not ideal ‚Äî Enter Layer 2 solutions. 

Popular ones include Polygon, Immutable X, Arbitrum and Polkadot.

These are projects built on top of the Ethereum - with the intention of making transactions faster, more secure - and more scalable.

Ethereum is the most popular, and widely-used blockchain on the planet.

However, Ethereum has expensive gas fees, and very slow throughput. The Ethereum mainnet can only process 13 transactions per second.

(For comparison, Solana does 65,000 TPS)

Layer 2 solutions - what they are, and why they're so important.

Something that I‚Äôve noticed all of the most successful NFT projects have in common:

Organic growth.

BAYC, Doodles, WoW, Cool Cats, Azuki, PA, CloneX, mfers, Deadfellaz, etc etc.

No unsustainable hype tactics, engagement farming, no influencer pumps, etc. - avoid these types.

RT @ZZZAGABOND: Invest in brands, not projects.

Invest in artists, not copy pasters.
@LukasEllDee FOMO is not our friend üôè

And remember to unplug. Health is wealth. I struggle with this a lot too - developing this discipline is a top priority of mine for 2022.

We‚Äôre all in this together üôè

This space moves fast - you‚Äôll never be able to keep up with even 1% of what‚Äôs happening. Don‚Äôt try. It‚Äôs a formula for burnout.

Just focus on a handful of projects, protocols, or initiatives, etc that you‚Äôre most passionate about.

The quality of your relationships truly determines the quality of your life.

There‚Äôs no amount of ETH worth more than Time with your friends and loved ones.

I capitalize Time because it‚Äôs truly our most valuable asset.

Burnout is a real thing in the Web3 space. A few thoughts.

When you‚Äôre in it for yourself - a $ or follower number you want to achieve - you‚Äôre susceptible to burnout when momentum slows.

But when you do it in service of others, there‚Äôs a certain strength that comes to you.
